The paper deals with the problem of multi-person tracking from visual observations, which is a classic problem in computer vision (cs.CV). The proposed model is based on a Bayesian framework, which involves probabilistic modeling and inference, and it is optimized using a variational expectation-maximization algorithm, which is a common technique in machine learning (cs.LG). The model also involves object-birth and object-visibility processes, which are related to temporal modeling and event detection, respectively, and are relevant to artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The paper evaluates the proposed method on multiple datasets, which involves video processing and performance evaluation, and is related to multimedia (cs.MM). Finally, the paper discusses the application of the proposed method to human-robot interaction, which is a topic in robotics (cs.RO).
